Windowing:
 refers to grouping events by the time (windows / buckets) that share the same key.
 Some of the examples are :
     -calculating the total number orders placed every minute or hour or day or any other custom time interval.
     -calculating the total revenue generated every minute or hour or day
  We can also perform windowing at the second rates too.


In order to group event by the time we need to extract the time from the Kafka record that's present on the Kafka topic.
1-Even time.
    The time the record gets produced into the Kafka topic.
    This time is set by the Kafka producer itself. This is a time which is the actual event generation time.
2-Ingestion Time:
  The time the record get appended to kafka topics

3-Processing Time:
 The time the record gets read and  processed by stream app

 TimeStamp Extractor in KafkaStream:

def:
Timestamp Extractor = "Clock picker"
- Kafka Streams needs a timestamp from each record
- "Where do I get the time from this message?"
- Extractor answers: "Here it is!" → picks the timestamp

Why does it matter?
Windows need timestamps:
- Tumbling: "Does this go in 10:00-10:05 window?"
- Hopping: "Which overlapping window?"
- Without timestamp → NO windows work!

type of time:
